Services, not containers.

The Swarm primitive isn't a container; it's a service, which is a declaration. It says: I want N replicas of image X across the cluster, with these networks, secrets, environment, resources, and update policy. Make it so. Swarm decomposes a service into tasks, one per replica, schedules each task onto a node, and creates a container to run it. The container is just an implementation detail; you reason at the service level.

So you run, docker service create, replicas three, name web, publish eighty-eighty to eighty, n-ginx. Docker service list shows web as replicated, three out of three. And docker service p-s web shows the individual tasks, and which node each one is on.

The payoff is self-healing. If a node hosting a task crashes, the manager notices, reschedules that task elsewhere, and three out of three is restored automatically, with nobody paged. That reconciliation loop is the entire point of an orchestrator.

There are two service modes. Replicated is the default: N tasks, and the scheduler picks where; that's the ninety-percent case. Global runs exactly one task per node, used for per-node agents, like log shippers or monitoring.

The service is also the unit of every operation; the single-host verbs move up a level. Service create declares a service, and most docker run flags apply. Service list and service p-s show desired-versus-running, and per-task placement. Service scale changes the replica count. Service update changes the definition, triggering a rolling update, which is next. Service rollback reverts the last update. And service remove deletes it and all its tasks. Here's the mental shift: you don't stop or start a service. You scale it, to zero to stop it, or you update it. The state is desired, not imperative.
